> ‘peace’; borne by the 13th-century poet Gottfried von Strassburg."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gottfried II. von Sponheim was born in 1149, in Sponheim, Bad Kreuznach, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany, his father, Gottfried I. von Sponheim, was 25 and his mother, Mathilde de Lorraine, was 30. He married Mathilde von Veldenz. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1183, in his hometown, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1149–1183":"1149–1183","1151–1204":"1151–1204","1175–1218":"1175–1218","1125–1183":"1125–1183","1119–1182":"1119–1